## Problem Statement

Build a browser-based game in 60 minutes for the Cursor hackathon in SF.
The game: Claude API generates code snippets with one intentional bug. The player
clicks the buggy line before a 15-second timer hits zero. 10 rounds, score at end.

## What Makes This Cool

It's on-theme for a Cursor audience — developers who live in code. The mechanic is
instantly explainable: "spot the bug." The AI generates the puzzle; the player solves
it. That loop is fast, satisfying, and the "AI wrote a bug on purpose" angle lands
perfectly in a room full of engineers who've been burned by AI-generated bugs.

## Constraints

- Single HTML file, no build step
- Works via `open index.html` or GitHub Pages
- Claude API key entered at game load (input field) or hardcoded
- 60-minute total build + polish time
- Deploy: GitHub Pages or share the file directly

## Premises

1. Claude API key available at runtime (input at page load or hardcoded for the demo)
2. Single .html file — no backend, no node_modules, no build
3. No multiplayer — scores shared by screenshot

## Approaches Considered

### Approach A: Debug Dash (chosen)
Single HTML file. Claude generates a code snippet with one bug. Player clicks the
buggy line in 15 seconds. 10 rounds. Score + time bonus at end.
Effort: M (45 min build, 15 min polish) | Risk: Low

### Approach B: Cursor Maze
Canvas maze + Claude generates the next level live, with a narrative blurb.
Infinite levels, AI-driven story. Effort: L (50 min, tight timeline) | Risk: Medium

### Approach C: Wordless
Semantic word puzzle — Claude scores guesses by closeness to a hidden concept.
Novel mechanic, polished with time to spare. Effort: S (35 min build) | Risk: Low

## Recommended Approach

Debug Dash. Most on-theme for Cursor's audience, instantly explainable to any
developer in the room, and the "Claude deliberately wrote a bug" angle is a
genuinely funny and memorable use of the API.

## Open Questions

- Snippet languages: **default to JS-only** for the core build; add language variety
  (Python/Go/TypeScript) as a stretch goal after the core loop works.
- Bug granularity: line-level click is ~10x easier to build than character-level and
  still fun. Stick with line-level.

## Success Criteria

- Game loads in browser with no errors
- 10 rounds complete end-to-end without 429 rate limit errors
- Score screen shows at the end
- Shareable: another person can play from a file or GitHub Pages URL

## Distribution Plan

- **Demo day:** open the .html file directly or push to GitHub Pages
  (`gh-pages` branch or `/docs` folder in a new public repo)
- **API key:** visible `<input type="password">` at game load — no secrets in the URL

